<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Chicken Note</div>
<div class="nbunit" id="edn143">  143  Shem's &lsquo;first riddle of the universe&rsquo; reappears at 275.31 (356.12) <i>the farst wriggle from the ubivence, whereom is man, that old offender, nother man, wheile he is asame</i>; at 384.23 (495.06) <i>Sylphing me when is a maid nought a maid</i>; and at 474.07 (607.11) <i>The first and last rittlerattle of the anniverse: when is a nam nought a nam whenas it is a. Watch!</i> In the notebooks the question is associated with Shem, with God (see <a name="sd2759i" href="../fnbs/sd2all.htm#sd2759i">SD2 (VI.A):759(i)</a>) and, curiously, with Leopold Bloom (see <a name="n03030b" href="../fnbs/n03all.htm#n03030b">N3 (VI.B.3):030(b)</a>). Shem seems to be pondering his masculinity.  </div>
